\begin_layout Enumerate
First, let us write the solution of the recurrence in a simpler form: 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{y}_{2}=A\vec{y}_{1}=A^{2}\vec{y}_{0}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{y}_{3}=A\vec{y}_{2}=A^{3}\vec{y}_{0}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\ldots$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{y}_{n}=A^{n}\vec{y}_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 (You can also prove this more formally by induction, but the pattern is
 obvious.)
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is diagonalizable, we can write 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{y}_{0}$
\end_inset

 in the basis of the eigenvectors: 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{y}_{0}=\sum_{k}c_{k}\vec{x}_{k}$
\end_inset

 for some coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{k}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{y}_{n}=A^{n}\vec{y}_{0}=\sum_{k}c_{k}\lambda_{k}^{n}\vec{x}_{n}$
\end_inset

, since 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{n}$
\end_inset

 simply multiplies each eigenvector by 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 However, all of the eigenvalues have 
\begin_inset Formula $|\lambda|<1$
\end_inset

 except for 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{0}=1$
\end_inset

, which means that 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda^{n}\to0$
\end_inset

 for large 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, for large 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, everything except for the 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}_{0}$
\end_inset

 term goes to zero, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{y}_{n}\approx c_{0}\vec{x}_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 However, we can be more explicit than this because 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 was given to be symmetric in this part, which means that the eigenvectors
 are orthogonal and we can write 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{k}=\frac{\vec{x}_{k}^{T}\vec{y}_{0}}{\vec{x}_{k}^{T}\vec{x}_{k}}$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, 
\begin_inset Formula $\boxed{\vec{y}_{n}\approx\frac{\vec{x}_{0}^{T}\vec{y}_{0}}{\vec{x}_{0}^{T}\vec{x}_{0}}\vec{x}_{0}=\frac{\vec{x}_{0}\vec{x}_{0}^{T}}{\vec{x}_{0}^{T}\vec{x}_{0}}\vec{y}_{0}}$
\end_inset

 for large 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

, where for aesthetic reasons I rewrote it in the form of a projection matrix
 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}_{0}\vec{x}_{0}^{T}/\vec{x}_{0}^{T}\vec{x}_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 If you want, you could use a more accurate approximation, and write 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{y}_{n}$
\end_inset

 as the sum of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}_{0}$
\end_inset

 term plus the lowest-order correction by including the next-biggest term
 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}_{1}$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{y}_{n}\approx\left[\frac{\vec{x}_{0}\vec{x}_{0}^{T}}{\vec{x}_{0}^{T}\vec{x}_{0}}+\frac{1}{2^{n}}\frac{\vec{x}_{1}\vec{x}_{1}^{T}}{\vec{x}_{1}^{T}\vec{x}_{1}}\right]\vec{y}_{0}$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

Note that you can 
\emph on
not
\emph default
 assume that the eigenvectors are normalized to length = 1, i.e.
 you cannot assume here that 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}_{0}^{T}\vec{x}_{0}=\Vert\vec{x}_{0}\Vert^{2}=1$
\end_inset

.
 Although one can always 
\emph on
choose
\emph default
 the eigenvectors to be scaled in this way, it is not 
\emph on
automatic
\emph default
, and their length was not specified in this problem.
\end_layout

