\begin_layout Enumerate
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}$
\end_inset

 is an eigenvector of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $A\vec{x}=\lambda\vec{x}$
\end_inset

.
 Take the dot product of both sides with 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}$
\end_inset

 , i.e.
 multiply both sides with 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}^{*}=\overline{\vec{x}^{T}}$
\end_inset

 (noting that we 
\emph on
cannot
\emph default
 assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}$
\end_inset

 is real), obtaining: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray*}
\vec{x}^{*}A\vec{x} & = & \lambda\vec{x}^{*}\vec{x}=\lambda\Vert\vec{x}\Vert^{2}\\
 & = & \left(A^{*}\vec{x}\right)^{*}\vec{x}\\
 & = & (-A\vec{x})^{*}\vec{x}=(-\lambda\vec{x})^{*}\vec{x}=-\bar{\lambda}\Vert\vec{x}\Vert^{2},\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

where in the third line we have used the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is real-antisymmetric, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $A^{*}=A^{T}=-A$
\end_inset

.
 Then, since by definition an eigenvector has 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}\neq0$
\end_inset

 and thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\Vert\vec{x}\Vert\neq0$
\end_inset

, by comparing the first and third lines we obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $\boxed{\lambda=-\bar{\lambda}}$
\end_inset

, and hence the eigenvalue is purely imaginary.
\end_layout

