\begin_layout Enumerate
The eigenfunctions must still be sines, cosines, or exponentials, as noted
 in class, with the boundary conditions determining which one.
 
\begin_inset Formula $u(0)=0$
\end_inset

 means that they must be sines.
 To get 
\begin_inset Formula $u'(L)=0$
\end_inset

, they must reach a maximum or a minimum at 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 (a phase that is an odd multiple of 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi/2$
\end_inset

), i.e.
 the eigenfunctions must be of the form: 
\begin_inset Formula \[
u_{n}(x)=\sin\left[\left(n+\frac{1}{2}\right)\frac{\pi x}{L}\right]\]

\end_inset

for integers 
\begin_inset Formula $n=0,1,2,\ldots$
\end_inset

, with corresponding eigenvalues 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{n}=-[(n+\frac{1}{2})\frac{\pi}{L}]^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 (Of course, any constant multiple of this works as well, as well as 
\begin_inset Formula $n<0$
\end_inset

, but those variations do not give linearly independent solutions.) We can
 check that these are orthogonal, using the trig.
 identity 
\begin_inset Formula $\sin A\sin B=[\cos(A-B)-\cos(A+B)]/2$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray*}
\int_{0}^{L}u_{n}(x)u_{m}(x)dx & = & \frac{1}{2}\int_{0}^{L}\left[\cos\left((n-m)\frac{\pi x}{L}\right)-\cos\left((n+m+1)\frac{\pi x}{L}\right)\right]dx\\
 & = & \frac{L}{2\pi}\left[\left.\frac{\sin\left((n-m)\frac{\pi x}{L}\right)}{n-m}-\frac{\sin\left((n+m+1)\frac{\pi x}{L}\right)}{n+m+1}\right|_{0}^{L}\right]\\
 & = & 0\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

for 
\begin_inset Formula $n\neq m$
\end_inset

 (and hence distinct eigenvalues 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{n}\neq\lambda_{m}$
\end_inset

), since the sine of any integer multiple of 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 is zero.
\end_layout

